  coaching_execution = '{"movement_description":"Single-Leg Kettlebell RDL trains single-leg posterior-chain strength with pelvis and trunk control using kettlebell resistance. The athlete organizes the body first, creates tension through the handle and floor, moves through a range they own, and stops the set before technique breaks.","setup":["Place the kettlebell(s) close enough that the athlete can reach without rounding.","Set the feet, hinge the hips, pack the shoulders, and brace before loading the handle.","Create tension through the floor and handle before the bell leaves the ground or changes direction."],"execution_steps":["Push the floor away and extend the hips while keeping the kettlebell close.","Reach the top with glutes and trunk engaged, not with the ribs flared.","Lower by hinging the hips back while the spine stays long and the handle path stays controlled.","Reset tension before each rep instead of bouncing or rushing."],"coach_cues":["Own the start before the rep starts.","Strong, controlled, repeatable.","Brace, then move the bell.","Hips back, spine long, bell close.","Finish tall with glutes, not low-back arch."],"athlete_cues":["Strong and clean beats heavy and sloppy.","Stop before the bell controls you.","Make the last rep look like the first rep."],"breathing_cues":["Inhale to prepare and brace before the hard part.","Exhale through the effort without losing trunk position.","Do not use long breath holds with youth, beginners, older adults, or pregnancy/postpartum athletes."],"common_faults":["Chasing load after position quality breaks.","Turning the set into a rushed conditioning station instead of strength work.","Rounding the back or reaching the bell away from the body.","Squatting the hinge when the goal is posterior-chain loading."],"quality_gate":["Pain-free range of motion.","Kettlebell path stays controlled.","Posture remains organized under load.","Athlete can stop the set before grip or alignment fails."],"stop_signs":["Sharp pain or joint pinching.","Grip becomes unsafe or bell path becomes uncontrolled.","Spine, shoulder, hip, knee, ankle, or wrist position cannot be maintained.","Breath-holding, dizziness, or pressure symptoms dominate the set."]}'::jsonb,
