  coaching_execution = '{"movement_description":"Kettlebell Front-Rack Carry trains trunk and shoulder strength under a front-rack load while walking tall using kettlebell resistance. The athlete organizes the body first, creates tension through the handle and floor, moves through a range they own, and stops the set before technique breaks.","setup":["Choose a clear walking lane with enough space to stop safely.","Pick up the kettlebell(s) with a hinge, pack the shoulders, and stand tall before moving.","Set ribs over pelvis, eyes forward, and grip the handle without shrugging or leaning."],"execution_steps":["Stand tall with the kettlebell(s) under control before the first step.","Walk with quiet, short-to-moderate steps while keeping ribs stacked and shoulders packed.","Keep the bell path stable and avoid leaning, rushing, or turning the carry into conditioning.","Set the bell down with a hinge only after posture and grip are still controlled."],"coach_cues":["Own the start before the rep starts.","Strong, controlled, repeatable.","Brace, then move the bell.","Walk tall; bell quiet; ribs over pelvis.","Small strong steps, no lean."],"athlete_cues":["Strong and clean beats heavy and sloppy.","Stop before the bell controls you.","Make the last rep look like the first rep."],"breathing_cues":["Inhale to prepare and brace before the hard part.","Exhale through the effort without losing trunk position.","Do not use long breath holds with youth, beginners, older adults, or pregnancy/postpartum athletes."],"common_faults":["Chasing load after position quality breaks.","Turning the set into a rushed conditioning station instead of strength work.","Leaning away from the load or letting the shoulders ride up.","Walking too fast and losing posture before the target distance."],"quality_gate":["Pain-free range of motion.","Kettlebell path stays controlled.","Posture remains organized under load.","Athlete can stop the set before grip or alignment fails."],"stop_signs":["Sharp